T1  - Financial contracts as lasting commitments: The case of a leveraged oligopoly
AU  - Fulghieri, Paolo
AU  - Nagarajan, S
JO  - Journal of Financial Intermediation
VL  - 2
IS  - 1
SP  - 2
EP  - 32
PY  - 1992
DA  - 1992/03/01/
SN  - 1042-9573
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/1042-9573(92)90018-9
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/1042957392900189
AB  - The commitment value of financial contracts is limited by the ability of contracting parties to renegotiate them away, if it becomes mutually beneficial to do so. When debt contracts are used by oligopolistic firms to commit to aggressive output strategies as in Brander-Lewis, we show that renegotiation may undermine commitment under symmetric information, but not generally under asymmetric information. Lasting contracts that survive renegotiation are proposed. It is shown that there exist lasting debt contracts which preserve the commitment value and in which not all debt is renegotiated away.
ER  - 
